            <h1>4. Evolutionary Threat Simulation</h1>
        </header>

        <section class="category-article" style="margin-bottom: 40px; font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8;">
            <p>The Threat Simulation Theory (TST) posits that dreams evolved as a survival mechanism. By simulating dangerous scenarios—being chased, attacked, or social failure—the brain rehearses responses in a safe environment. This strengthens the fight-or-flight reflex for real-world threats. Analyzing nightmares through this evolutionary lens reveals that many "scary" dreams are actually adaptive biological exercises designed to sharpen our ancestral survival instincts.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="category-wp-content">
<figure class="wp-block-uagb-image__figure"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="/media-images/posts/evolutionary-nightmares-illustration-1.webp" alt="Illustration for 4. Evolutionary Threat Simulation" class="uag-image-1571" width="1200" height="550" title="4. Evolutionary Threat Simulation" role="img"></figure>
</section>



